{"title_page": "Back Street Crawler (band)", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=July 2009}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Back Street Crawler\n| image                 = \n| caption            = \n| image_size            = \n| background          = group_or_band\n| alias               = \n| origin              = [[United States]]\n| genre               = [[Blues rock]], [[hard rock]], [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]], [[Rock music]]\n| years_active        = 1975\u20131976\n| label               = [[Atlantic Records]]\n| associated_acts     = [[Paul Kossoff]], [[Crawler (band)|Crawler]], [[Free (band)|Free]]\n| website                 = \n| past_members        = [[Paul Kossoff]]<br />[[Terry Wilson-Slesser|Terry Slesser]]<br />[[Terry Wilson (musician)|Terry Wilson]]<br />[[Tony Braunagel]]<br />Mike Montgomery<br />[[John Bundrick|John 'Rabbit' Bundrick]]\n}}\n\n'''Back Street Crawler''' was an English\u2013American rock band There was a group of blues and rock musicians founded by guitarist [[Paul Kossoff]] (ex-[[Free (band)|Free]]), signing to [[Atlantic Records]] (courtesy of [[Ahmet Erteg\u00fcn]]) in 1975.  The band took the name from Kossoff's solo album, ''[[Back Street Crawler (Paul Kossoff album)|Back Street Crawler]]''. [[Terry Wilson (musician)|Terry Wilson]], Mike Montgomery and [[Tony Braunagel]] had played together in the short lived Bloontz, whose only album was released in 1973 and included versions of the Mike Montgomery songs, \"Jason Blue\" and \"The Band Plays On\", both of which featured on Back Street Crawler's album ''[[The Band Plays On (Back Street Crawler album)|The Band Plays On]]''.\n\n== History ==\nThe band's progress would continually be overshadowed by Kossoff's well publicised drug dependency.  His reliance on narcotics was common knowledge.  Ultimately, his addiction to narcotics led to his eventual demise.\n\nA headlining tour was conducted in the UK during May and June 1975, prior to finalising sessions for the album ''[[The Band Plays On (Back Street Crawler album)|The Band Plays On]]''. To push the album, a further series of live dates were announced. However, these shows were curtailed when Kossoff was taken ill with a stomach ulcer.  Whilst receiving treatment, Kossoff's condition worsened and suffered a cardiac arrest. Four live concerts, in [[Liverpool]], [[The Apollo (Glasgow)|Glasgow]], [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] and [[London]], were undertaken in November.\n\nKeyboard player Mike Montgomery quit the band shortly afterwards, to be replaced by [[John Bundrick|John 'Rabbit' Bundrick]] for a series of American concerts in early 1976. Again, ill-health on Kossoff's part, including the guitarist breaking his fingers, resulted in numerous shows being cancelled.\n\nThe band set to work on their second album, working with producer [[Glyn Johns]], in a variety of studios in New York and Los Angeles. With Kossoff still obviously ailing, session musician [[W. G. Walden|W.G. 'Snuffy' Walden]] committed much of the guitar to tape, Kossoff later playing lead over the mostly completed tracks. Walden also performed live, in the absence of Kossoff, with the band in February 1976. With Kossoff resuming his position, the band headlined four shows at the [[Starwood (nightclub)|Starwood]] in [[West Hollywood, California|West Hollywood]]. During the run of shows, [[Bad Company]], were performing at the [[The Forum (Inglewood, California)|Los Angeles Forum]] and they joined Back Street Crawler onstage for two nights. The final night of the engagement, on March 3, 1976, was to be the final performance of both Paul Kossoff and Back Street Crawler.\n\nA British tour with AC/DC as support act was set to commence on April 25, 1976. On March 19, Paul Kossoff died from cerebral and pulmonary [[edema]] on an overnight flight from Los Angeles to New York.  Following Kossoff's death, the band continued under the name of [[Crawler (band)|Crawler]].\n\n=== Band members ===\n* [[Paul Kossoff]] \u2013 lead guitar (1975\u20131976; died 1976)\n* [[Terry Wilson-Slesser]] \u2013 lead vocals (1975\u20131976)\n* [[Terry Wilson (musician)|Terry Wilson]] \u2013 bass guitar (1975\u20131976)\n* [[Tony Braunagel]] \u2013 drums (1975\u20131976)\n* Mike Montgomery \u2013 keyboards (1975\u20131976)\n* [[John Bundrick]] \u2013 keyboards (1976)\n\n== Albums ==\n* 1975&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[The Band Plays On (Back Street Crawler album)|The Band Plays On]]'' ([[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]])\n* 1976&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[2nd Street (album)|2nd Street]]'' (Atlantic)\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.terryslesser.com Terry Wilson-Slesser]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Back Street Crawler (band)}}\n[[Category:Atlantic Records artists]]\n[[Category:Atco Records artists]]\n[[Category:British blues musical groups]]\n[[Category:British hard rock musical groups]]\n[[Category:British heavy metal musical groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from London]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1975]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 1976]]\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=July 2009}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Back Street Crawler\n| image                 = \n| caption            = \n| image_size            = \n| background          = group_or_band\n| alias               = \n| origin              = [[London]], [[England]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| genre               = [[Blues rock]], [[hard rock]], [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]], [[Rock music]]\n| years_active        = 1975\u20131976\n* 2020 \u2013 present\n| label               = [[Atlantic Records]]\n| associated_acts     = [[Paul Kossoff]], [[Crawler (band)|Crawler]], [[Spooky Tooth]], [[Foreigner (band)|Foreigner]], [[Free (band)|Free]]\n| website                 = \n| current_members     = [[Dennis Elliott]]<br />[[Lou Gramm]]<br />[[Mick Jones (Foreigner guitarist)|Mick Jones]]<br />[[Tony Kaye (musician)|Tony Kaye]]<br />[[Ian McDonald (musician)|Ian McDonald]]<br />[[Rick Wills]]\n| past_members        = [[Paul Kossoff]]<br />[[Terry Wilson-Slesser|Terry Slesser]]<br />[[Terry Wilson (musician)|Terry Wilson]]<br />[[Tony Braunagel]]<br />Mike Montgomery<br />[[John Bundrick|John 'Rabbit' Bundrick]]\n}}\n\n'''Back Street Crawler''' were an English\u2013American rock band based in London in 1975. There was a group of blues and rock musicians founded by guitarist [[Paul Kossoff]] (ex-[[Free (band)|Free]]), signing to [[Atlantic Records]] (courtesy of [[Ahmet Erteg\u00fcn]]) in 1975.  The band took the name from Kossoff's solo album, ''[[Back Street Crawler (Paul Kossoff album)|Back Street Crawler]]''. [[Terry Wilson (musician)|Terry Wilson]], Mike Montgomery and [[Tony Braunagel]] had played together in the short lived Bloontz, whose only album was released in 1973 and included versions of the Mike Montgomery songs, \"Jason Blue\" and \"The Band Plays On\", both of which featured on Back Street Crawler's album ''[[The Band Plays On (Back Street Crawler album)|The Band Plays On]]''.\n\n== History ==\nThe band's progress would continually be overshadowed by Kossoff's well publicised drug dependency.  His reliance on narcotics was common knowledge.  Ultimately, his addiction to narcotics led to his eventual demise.\n\nA headlining tour was conducted in the UK during May and June 1975, prior to finalising sessions for the album ''[[The Band Plays On (Back Street Crawler album)|The Band Plays On]]''. To push the album, a further series of live dates were announced. However, these shows were curtailed when Kossoff was taken ill with a stomach ulcer.  Whilst receiving treatment, Kossoff's condition worsened and suffered a cardiac arrest. Four live concerts, in [[Liverpool]], [[The Apollo (Glasgow)|Glasgow]], [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] and [[London]], were undertaken in November.\n\nKeyboard player Mike Montgomery quit the band shortly afterwards, to be replaced by [[John Bundrick|John 'Rabbit' Bundrick]] for a series of American concerts in early 1976. Again, ill-health on Kossoff's part, including the guitarist breaking his fingers, resulted in numerous shows being cancelled.\n\nThe band set to work on their second album, working with producer [[Glyn Johns]], in a variety of studios in New York and Los Angeles. With Kossoff still obviously ailing, session musician [[W. G. Walden|W.G. 'Snuffy' Walden]] committed much of the guitar to tape, Kossoff later playing lead over the mostly completed tracks. Walden also performed live, in the absence of Kossoff, with the band in February 1976. With Kossoff resuming his position, the band headlined four shows at the [[Starwood (nightclub)|Starwood]] in [[West Hollywood, California|West Hollywood]]. During the run of shows, [[Bad Company]], were performing at the [[The Forum (Inglewood, California)|Los Angeles Forum]] and they joined Back Street Crawler onstage for two nights. The final night of the engagement, on March 3, 1976, was to be the final performance of both Paul Kossoff and Back Street Crawler.\n\nA British tour with AC/DC as support act was set to commence on April 25, 1976. On March 19, Paul Kossoff died from cerebral and pulmonary [[edema]] on an overnight flight from Los Angeles to New York.  Following Kossoff's death, the band continued under the name of [[Crawler (band)|Crawler]].\n\n== Members ==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n=== Main lineups ===\n* [[Lou Gramm]] \u2013 lead vocals, percussion (2020\u2013present)\n* [[Dennis Elliott]] \u2013 drums (2020\u2013present)\n* [[Mick Jones (Foreigner guitarist)|Mick Jones]] \u2013 lead guitar, backing vocals (2020\u2013present)\n* [[Tony Kaye (musician)|Tony Kaye]] \u2013 keyboards (2020\u2013present)\n* [[Ian McDonald (musician)|Ian McDonald]] \u2013 saxophone, flute, keyboards, rhythm guitar, backing vocals (2020\u2013present)\n* [[Rick Wills]] \u2013 bass, backing vocals (2020\u2013present)\n{{col-break}}\n=== Former members ===\n* [[Paul Kossoff]] \u2013 lead guitar (1975\u20131976; died 1976)\n* [[Terry Wilson-Slesser]] \u2013 lead vocals (1975\u20131976)\n* [[Terry Wilson (musician)|Terry Wilson]] \u2013 bass guitar (1975\u20131976)\n* [[Tony Braunagel]] \u2013 drums (1975\u20131976)\n* Mike Montgomery \u2013 keyboards (1975\u20131976)\n* [[John Bundrick]] \u2013 keyboards (1976)\n{{col-end}}\n\n== Albums ==\n* 1975&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[The Band Plays On (Back Street Crawler album)|The Band Plays On]]'' ([[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]])\n* 1976&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[2nd Street (album)|2nd Street]]'' (Atlantic)\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.terryslesser.com Terry Wilson-Slesser]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Back Street Crawler (band)}}\n[[Category:Atlantic Records artists]]\n[[Category:Atco Records artists]]\n[[Category:British blues musical groups]]\n[[Category:British hard rock musical groups]]\n[[Category:British heavy metal musical groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from London]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1975]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 1976]]\n[[Category:Musical groups reestablished in 2020]]\n", "name_user": "188.141.87.103", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eBand members =)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Back_Street_Crawler_(band)"}
{"title_page": "Ruby (given name)", "text_new": "{{Infobox Given Name Revised\n| name = Ruby\n| image=Cut Ruby.jpg\n| imagesize=200\n| caption=The name Ruby is taken from the name of the gemstone [[ruby]].\n| pronunciation= {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|r|u\u02d0|b|i}} {{respell|ROO|bee}}\n| gender = female\n| meaning = \"[[ruby]]\"\n| region = \n| nickname = \n| origin = [[Latin language|Latin]]\n| related names = Reuben, Rubi\n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Ruby''' is a predominantly feminine [[given name]] taken from the name of the [[gemstone]] [[ruby]]. The name of the gemstone comes from the [[Latin language|Latin]] ''ruber'', meaning ''[[red (color)|red]]''. The ruby is the [[birthstone]] for the month of July.<ref>[http://www.behindthename.com/name/ruby Behind the Name]</ref> \n\nThe name first came into wide use for girls in the late [[Victorian era]] along with other jewel names. \n\n==Popularity==\nRuby is a currently popular name in [[English language|English]]-speaking countries. It was the second most popular name given to baby girls in [[England]] and [[Wales]] in 2009, was the 24th most popular name given to baby girls born in [[Scotland]] in 2009; was the 17th most popular name for girls in [[Ireland]] in 2009; was the second most popular name for girls in [[New Zealand]] in 2009; was among [[List_of_most_popular_given_names#Female_names_5|the top five names given to girls in several]] [[Australia|Australian]] states in 2009, 2010 and 2013; and was the 108th most popular name given to baby girls born in the [[United States]] in 2009. The name was also once rarely given to boys in the United States and was ranked in the top 1,000 names given to boys born in that country between 1900 and 1940. In its masculine form, it is occasionally used as a nickname for the name [[Reuben]].<ref>[http://www.behindthename.com/top/search.php?terms=ruby Behind the Name]</ref>\n\nAuthors Pamela Redmond Satran and Linda Rosenkrantz noted in their 2007 book ''Baby Name Bible'' that Ruby is a \"vibrant\" name with a \"sassy and [[sultry]]\" image,<ref>Rosenkrantz, Linda, and Satran, Pamela Redmond (2007). ''The Baby Name Bible''. St. Martin's Griffin. {{ISBN|978-0-312-35220-2}}, p. 244</ref>\nwhile [[Laura Wattenberg]] wrote in her 2005 book ''The Baby Name Wizard: A Magical Method for Finding the Perfect Name For Your Baby'' that Ruby has the image of a woman \"kicking up her heels\" at a [[music hall]].<ref>Wattenberg, Laura (2005). ''The Baby Name Wizard: A Magical Method for Finding the Perfect Name For Your Baby''.  Broadway. {{ISBN|0-7679-1752-9}}</ref> \n\n== Notable people ==\nNotable people with the name include:\n\n* [[Ruby Bradley]] (1907\u20132002), Army nurse\n* [[Ruby Bridges]] (born 1954), American activist, first black child to attend an all-white elementary school in Louisiana in the 20th century\n* [[Ruby Dandridge]] (1900-1987), actress\n* [[Ruby Dee]] (1924\u20132014), actress\n* [[Ruby Dhalla]] (born 1974), Canadian politician\n* [[Ruby Nash Garnett]] (born 1939), lead singer of American group ''[[Ruby & the Romantics]]''\n* [[Ruby Gilbert]] (1929-2010), American politician\n* [[Ruby Goldstein]] (\"Ruby the Jewel of the Ghetto\"; 1907\u201384), American welterweight boxer and referee\n* [[Ruby Keeler]] (1910\u20131993), actress, singer and dancer\n* [[Ruby Laffoon]] (1869\u20131941), 43rd [[Governor of Kentucky]]\n* [[Ruby Lin]] (born 1976), Taiwanese actress\n* [[Ruby McKim]] (1891\u20131976), English quilt designer, entrepreneur, and writer\n* [[Ruby Modine]], American actress and singer\n* [[Ruby Murray]] (1935\u20131996), Northern Irish singer\n* [[Ruby Myers]] (1907\u20131983), also known as Sulochana, Indian silent film actress\n* [[Ruby Payne-Scott]] (1912\u20131981), pioneering Australian astronomer\n* [[Ruby Rose]] (born 1986), Australian MTV VJ\n* [[Ruby Riott]] (born 1991), ring name of American professional wrestler Dori Prange\n* [[Ruby Rubacuori]] (born 1993), Karima el Mahroug, allegedly had sex with the Italian prime minister Silvio Berlusconi when underage\n* [[Ruby (Egyptian singer)|Ruby]] (born 1981), real name Rania Hussein Muhammad Tawfiq, Egyptian singer, actress and model\n* [[Ruby Schleicher]] (born 1998), Australian rules footballer\n* [[Ruby Walsh]] (born 1979), Irish jockey\n* [[Ruby Wax]] (born 1953), comedian\n* [[Ruby Winters]] (1942\u20132016), American soul singer\n* [[Ruby Yang]], Chinese-American filmmaker\n*[[Ruby Oultram]] a famous furry, she starred in the movie 'no shame' \n\n===Fictional characters===\n* [[Ruby Kurosawa]], a character from the media-mix project ''Love Live! Sunshine!!''\n* [[List of RWBY characters#Ruby Rose|Ruby Rose]], the main protagonist of the animated web series ''[[RWBY]]''\n*Ruby, the main character from the [[Max & Ruby]] TV Series\n*Ruby, a character from the Cartoon Network TV series ''[[Steven Universe]]''\n*Ruby, a character from the cartoon ''[[Trollz]]''\n*Ruby, a (male) character in the ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Adventures]]'' manga series\n*Ruby, a demon character from the CW TV series ''[[Supernatural]]''\n*[[Ruby Dobbs]], a character in UK soap opera ''[[Coronation Street]]''\n*Ruby Spark, a character in UK drama ''[[Casualty (series)|Casualty]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{given name}}\n\n[[Category:English given names]]\n[[Category:Feminine given names]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Given Name Revised\n| name = Ruby\n| image=Cut Ruby.jpg\n| imagesize=200\n| caption=The name Ruby is taken from the name of the gemstone [[ruby]].\n| pronunciation= {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|r|u\u02d0|b|i}} {{respell|ROO|bee}}\n| gender = female\n| meaning = \"[[ruby]]\"\n| region = \n| nickname = \n| origin = [[Latin language|Latin]]\n| related names = Reuben, Rubi\n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Ruby''' is a predominantly feminine [[given name]] taken from the name of the [[gemstone]] [[ruby]]. The name of the gemstone comes from the [[Latin language|Latin]] ''ruber'', meaning ''[[red (color)|red]]''. The ruby is the [[birthstone]] for the month of July.<ref>[http://www.behindthename.com/name/ruby Behind the Name]</ref> \n\nThe name first came into wide use for girls in the late [[Victorian era]] along with other jewel names. \n\n==Popularity==\nRuby is a currently popular name in [[English language|English]]-speaking countries. It was the second most popular name given to baby girls in [[England]] and [[Wales]] in 2009, was the 24th most popular name given to baby girls born in [[Scotland]] in 2009; was the 17th most popular name for girls in [[Ireland]] in 2009; was the second most popular name for girls in [[New Zealand]] in 2009; was among [[List_of_most_popular_given_names#Female_names_5|the top five names given to girls in several]] [[Australia|Australian]] states in 2009, 2010 and 2013; and was the 108th most popular name given to baby girls born in the [[United States]] in 2009. The name was also once rarely given to boys in the United States and was ranked in the top 1,000 names given to boys born in that country between 1900 and 1940. In its masculine form, it is occasionally used as a nickname for the name [[Reuben]].<ref>[http://www.behindthename.com/top/search.php?terms=ruby Behind the Name]</ref>\n\nAuthors Pamela Redmond Satran and Linda Rosenkrantz noted in their 2007 book ''Baby Name Bible'' that Ruby is a \"vibrant\" name with a \"sassy and [[sultry]]\" image,<ref>Rosenkrantz, Linda, and Satran, Pamela Redmond (2007). ''The Baby Name Bible''. St. Martin's Griffin. {{ISBN|978-0-312-35220-2}}, p. 244</ref>\nwhile [[Laura Wattenberg]] wrote in her 2005 book ''The Baby Name Wizard: A Magical Method for Finding the Perfect Name For Your Baby'' that Ruby has the image of a woman \"kicking up her heels\" at a [[music hall]].<ref>Wattenberg, Laura (2005). ''The Baby Name Wizard: A Magical Method for Finding the Perfect Name For Your Baby''.  Broadway. {{ISBN|0-7679-1752-9}}</ref> \n\n== Notable people ==\nNotable people with the name include:\n\n* [[Ruby Bradley]] (1907\u20132002), Army nurse\n* [[Ruby Bridges]] (born 1954), American activist, first black child to attend an all-white elementary school in Louisiana in the 20th century\n* [[Ruby Dandridge]] (1900-1987), actress\n* [[Ruby Dee]] (1924\u20132014), actress\n* [[Ruby Dhalla]] (born 1974), Canadian politician\n* [[Ruby Nash Garnett]] (born 1939), lead singer of American group ''[[Ruby & the Romantics]]''\n* [[Ruby Gilbert]] (1929-2010), American politician\n* [[Ruby Goldstein]] (\"Ruby the Jewel of the Ghetto\"; 1907\u201384), American welterweight boxer and referee\n* [[Ruby Keeler]] (1910\u20131993), actress, singer and dancer\n* [[Ruby Laffoon]] (1869\u20131941), 43rd [[Governor of Kentucky]]\n* [[Ruby Lin]] (born 1976), Taiwanese actress\n* [[Ruby McKim]] (1891\u20131976), English quilt designer, entrepreneur, and writer\n* [[Ruby Modine]], American actress and singer\n* [[Ruby Murray]] (1935\u20131996), Northern Irish singer\n* [[Ruby Myers]] (1907\u20131983), also known as Sulochana, Indian silent film actress\n* [[Ruby Payne-Scott]] (1912\u20131981), pioneering Australian astronomer\n* [[Ruby Rose]] (born 1986), Australian MTV VJ\n* [[Ruby Riott]] (born 1991), ring name of American professional wrestler Dori Prange\n* [[Ruby Rubacuori]] (born 1993), Karima el Mahroug, allegedly had sex with the Italian prime minister Silvio Berlusconi when underage\n* [[Ruby (Egyptian singer)|Ruby]] (born 1981), real name Rania Hussein Muhammad Tawfiq, Egyptian singer, actress and model\n* [[Ruby Schleicher]] (born 1998), Australian rules footballer\n* [[Ruby Walsh]] (born 1979), Irish jockey\n* [[Ruby Wax]] (born 1953), comedian\n* [[Ruby Winters]] (1942\u20132016), American soul singer\n* [[Ruby Yang]], Chinese-American filmmaker\n\n===Fictional characters===\n* [[Ruby Kurosawa]], a character from the media-mix project ''Love Live! Sunshine!!''\n* [[List of RWBY characters#Ruby Rose|Ruby Rose]], the main protagonist of the animated web series ''[[RWBY]]''\n*Ruby, the main character from the [[Max & Ruby]] TV Series\n